This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it discusses the use of elasticity imaging to aid in the detection and diagnosis of pathological states. Additionally, the paper introduces a data-driven method for building neural network constitutive models (NNCMs) to learn stress-strain relationships from force-displacement data, which is a common approach in computer vision. 

The paper also discusses the use of quasi-static ultrasonic (US) elastography techniques, which are commonly used in biomedical imaging (cs.BIO). 

The use of neural networks to model stress-strain relationships is a common topic in machine learning (cs.LG) and neural networks (cs.NE). 

Finally, the paper discusses the reconstruction of a Young's modulus image, which is a type of medical imaging (cs.MM).
